{
  "response": "# Sortable Data Table Accessibility Design Plan\n\n> **For Claude:** Use a11y-planner protocol. Review with a11y-critic after implementation.  \n> **Compliance target:** WCAG 2.2 AA  \n> **Users who need accessibility:** Screen reader users, keyboard-only users, low vision users, screen magnifier users, high contrast mode users  \n> **Assistive technologies:** JAWS, NVDA, VoiceOver, keyboard-only navigation  \n\n**Feature:** A reusable React data table component with sortable column headers, visible sort indicators, optional pagination, and support for multiple tables on one page.  \n**Risk Level:** High  \n**Component/Page Type:** Semantic data table with sortable headers and optional pagination  \n\n---\n\n## Scope & Context\n\nThis plan covers a reusable data table for a React data visualization library. The table displays structured tabular data using native HTML table semantics and supports sorting by column headers. Sorting may be single-column by default, with an explicitly planned extension path for multi-column sorting.\n\nThe primary accessibility risk is not basic table semantics; it is the interaction layer around sorting, focus, state announcement, pagination, and large data sets. This plan does **not** claim that arrow-key spreadsheet navigation is required for every table. It claims that if arrow-key cell navigation is offered, it must be implemented as a deliberate enhanced interaction and not interfere with native screen reader table navigation.\n\nThe default recommendation is:\n\n- Use native table semantics, not ARIA table/grid roles.\n- Make only sortable column headers tabbable.\n- Use native `<button>` elements inside sortable `<th scope=\"col\">`.\n- Use `aria-sort` on the active sorted column header.\n- Use visible text/icon sort indicators with non-color alternatives.\n- Use pagination or virtualization carefully, with row count and page state communicated.\n\nWCAG basis: 1.3.1 Info and Relationships, 1.3.2 Meaningful Sequence, 2.1.1 Keyboard, 2.4.3 Focus Order, 2.4.6 Headings and Labels, 2.4.7 Focus Visible, 2.4.11 Focus Not Obscured, 2.4.13 Focus Appearance, 2.5.8 Target Size, 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value, 4.1.3 Status Messages.\n\n---\n\n## Semantic Structure Plan\n\nUse native HTML table elements:\n\n- `<table>` for tabular data only.\n- `<caption>` for table purpose and context.\n- `<thead>` for column headers.\n- `<tbody>` for body rows.\n- `<tfoot>` only if summary/footer data exists.\n- `<tr>` for rows.\n- `<th scope=\"col\">` for column headers.\n- `<th scope=\"row\">` for row-identifying cells when a row has a primary label.\n- `<td>` for data cells.\n\nDo **not** use `role=\"table\"`, `role=\"grid\"`, `role=\"row\"`, or `role=\"cell\"` unless native semantics are impossible. Native table semantics are more robust across JAWS, NVDA, and VoiceOver. This plan is **not** designing an editable spreadsheet grid.\n\nWCAG citations:\n\n- Native table structure and header associations: WCAG 1.3.1 Info and Relationships.\n- DOM order matching visual row/column order: WCAG 1.3.2 Meaningful Sequence.\n- Descriptive table caption and header labels: WCAG 2.4.6 Headings and Labels.\n\n### Structure Diagram\n\n```html\n<section aria-labelledby=\"table-heading\">\n  <h2 id=\"table-heading\">Revenue by Region</h2>\n\n  <div role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\" aria-atomic=\"true\">\n    Sort and pagination updates announced here.\n  </div>\n\n  <table>\n    <caption>\n      Revenue by region. Use sortable column headers to change the table order.\n    </caption>\n\n    <thead>\n      <tr>\n        <th scope=\"col\" aria-sort=\"ascending\">\n          <button type=\"button\">\n            Region\n            <span aria-hidden=\"true\">\u2191</span>\n            <span class=\"visually-hidden\">sorted ascending</span>\n          </button>\n        </th>\n\n        <th scope=\"col\">\n          <button type=\"button\">\n            Revenue\n            <span aria-hidden=\"true\">\u2195</span>\n            <span class=\"visually-hidden\">not sorted</span>\n          </button>\n        </th>\n\n        <th scope=\"col\">\n          <button type=\"button\">\n            Growth\n            <span aria-hidden=\"true\">\u2195</span>\n            <span class=\"visually-hidden\">not sorted</span>\n          </button>\n        </th>\n      </tr>\n    </thead>\n\n    <tbody>\n      <tr>\n        <th scope=\"row\">Northeast</th>\n        <td>$1.2M</td>\n        <td>8%</td>\n      </tr>\n    </tbody>\n  </table>\n\n  <nav aria-label=\"Table pagination\">\n    Pagination controls appear here when needed.\n  </nav>\n</section>\n```\n\nImportant boundary: if a visible icon is already backed by `aria-sort` and visually hidden text, the icon itself must be `aria-hidden=\"true\"` to avoid redundant announcements like \u201cup arrow\u201d or \u201cblack up-pointing triangle.\u201d WCAG 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value.\n\n---\n\n## Interaction Pattern Design\n\nThis component primarily uses native table semantics plus native button behavior. It should not be forced into APG Grid unless the product intentionally supports spreadsheet-style two-dimensional keyboard navigation, cell selection, editing, or complex row actions.\n\n### Interactive Elements Table\n\n| Widget | APG / Semantic Pattern | Keyboard Model | ARIA Attributes | WCAG Citation |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Sortable column header | Native table header + native button; related to APG Button pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/button/ | Tab to button; Enter/Space sorts column | `aria-sort` on sorted `<th>`; optional `aria-describedby` for instructions | 1.3.1, 2.1.1, 2.4.6, 4.1.2 |\n| Non-sortable column header | Native `<th scope=\"col\">` | Not tabbable unless it contains another control | No ARIA required | 1.3.1 |\n| Row header cell | Native `<th scope=\"row\">` when row has an identifying label | Screen reader table navigation announces row header with cells | No ARIA required | 1.3.1 |\n| Pagination nav | Native navigation landmark + buttons/links | Tab through controls; Enter/Space activates buttons | `aria-label`, `aria-current=\"page\"` where applicable, disabled state | 2.1.1, 2.4.4, 2.4.6, 4.1.2 |\n| Results/page status | Status message pattern | Not focusable by default | `role=\"status\"`, `aria-live=\"polite\"`, `aria-atomic=\"true\"` | 4.1.3 |\n\n### Sort Behavior\n\nDefault sort model: single-column sorting.\n\nCycle per sortable header:\n\n1. Not sorted \u2192 ascending.\n2. Ascending \u2192 descending.\n3. Descending \u2192 ascending.\n\nAvoid cycling back to \u201cnone\u201d unless product requirements explicitly need an unsorted original order. If \u201cnone\u201d exists, the reset behavior must be clear and announced.\n\nFor `aria-sort`:\n\n- Apply `aria-sort=\"ascending\"` to the sorted column\u2019s `<th>`.\n- Apply `aria-sort=\"descending\"` to the sorted column\u2019s `<th>`.\n- For unsorted columns, prefer omitting `aria-sort`.\n- If the implementation includes explicit \u201cnot sorted\u201d state, `aria-sort=\"none\"` is acceptable, but avoid putting `aria-sort=\"none\"` on every unsorted column if it creates noisy announcements.\n- For multi-column sorting, use `aria-sort=\"other\"` only when the sort order cannot be expressed as a single ascending or descending column. Also provide visible and programmatic explanation of the multi-sort priority.\n\nWCAG citation: `aria-sort` communicates state programmatically under WCAG 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value and preserves table relationships under WCAG 1.3.1 Info and Relationships.\n\n### Screen Reader Announcement Strategy\n\nOn focus, a sortable header button should communicate:\n\n- Column label.\n- Button role.\n- Current sort state.\n- Optional instruction, if needed: \u201cActivate to sort descending.\u201d\n\nExample expected experience:\n\n- \u201cRegion, button, sorted ascending.\u201d\n- \u201cRevenue, button, not sorted.\u201d\n- After activation: live region announces \u201cSorted by Revenue, ascending.\u201d\n\nDo not rely only on icon shape or background color to communicate sorted state. WCAG 1.4.1 Use of Color, 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value.\n\n---\n\n## Focus Management Plan\n\n### Default Tab Order\n\nRecommended tab model:\n\n1. Skip link to main content if the table appears in a full page layout.\n2. Table-level controls before the table, if present: search, filters, density controls.\n3. Sortable column header buttons, left to right.\n4. Row-level interactive controls, if cells contain links/buttons.\n5. Pagination controls after the table.\n\nDo **not** make every data cell tabbable by default. A 100-row table with 8 columns would create hundreds of tab stops and become unusable for keyboard users. Native screen reader table navigation already supports moving by row and column.\n\nWCAG citations:\n\n- Logical tab order: WCAG 2.4.3 Focus Order.\n- Keyboard operation of sorting and pagination: WCAG 2.1.1 Keyboard.\n- Avoid excessive keyboard burden: WCAG 2.4.3 Focus Order, 2.4.7 Focus Visible.\n\n### Sort Header Focus\n\nSortable headers use native `<button>` inside `<th>`. The button receives focus, not the `<th>`.\n\nFocus indicator requirements:\n\n- Visible on sortable header buttons.\n- At least 3:1 contrast against adjacent colors.\n- Meets WCAG 2.4.7 Focus Visible and WCAG 2.4.13 Focus Appearance.\n- Use a two-color focus treatment where possible so the indicator remains visible against varied header backgrounds.\n- Ensure sticky headers do not obscure focused controls. WCAG 2.4.11 Focus Not Obscured.\n\n### After Sorting\n\nWhen a user activates a sort button:\n\n- Keep focus on the activated sort button.\n- Update `aria-sort` on the relevant `<th>`.\n- Update the visible sort indicator.\n- Announce the new state through a single polite status region.\n\nDo not move focus into the body rows after sort by default. Sorting changes table order, but the user\u2019s current task is still controlling sort. Unexpected focus movement would disrupt keyboard and screen reader users. WCAG 2.4.3 Focus Order.\n\n### Optional Arrow-Key Navigation\n\nArrow-key navigation is optional and should only be included if the table is intended to feel like a data exploration surface.\n\nIf implemented:\n\n- Do not switch the table to ARIA Grid unless the component supports grid-like interaction and selection.\n- Prefer allowing native screen reader table shortcuts to work.\n- If custom arrow navigation is added, document it as an enhancement and test it with JAWS, NVDA, and VoiceOver.\n- Do not trap arrow keys when a focused cell contains an input, link, button, or other control.\n- Do not make all cells permanent tab stops.\n\nThis plan does **not** require roving tabindex for the base sortable table. Roving tabindex would be appropriate for an APG Grid pattern, not a standard readable data table.\n\n---\n\n## State Communication Design\n\n### State Communication Table\n\n| State | Visual Indicator | Programmatic Indicator | ARIA Attribute | WCAG Citation |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Column not sorted | Neutral icon/text such as \u201cnot sorted\u201d or bidirectional arrow | Header has no active sort state; optional hidden text says \u201cnot sorted\u201d | Omit `aria-sort` or use `aria-sort=\"none\"` | 4.1.2 |\n| Column sorted ascending | Up arrow plus text or hidden text; optional background emphasis | Sorted `<th>` exposes ascending state | `aria-sort=\"ascending\"` on `<th>` | 1.3.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Column sorted descending | Down arrow plus text or hidden text; optional background emphasis | Sorted `<th>` exposes descending state | `aria-sort=\"descending\"` on `<th>` | 1.3.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Multi-column sort | Numbered priority indicator, e.g. \u201c1\u201d, \u201c2\u201d, plus direction text | Explain sort priority in caption/status text | `aria-sort=\"other\"` only if needed | 1.3.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Sort update complete | Status text updates visually or remains visually hidden | Polite live region announces update | `role=\"status\"`, `aria-live=\"polite\"`, `aria-atomic=\"true\"` | 4.1.3 |\n| Loading rows | Spinner plus text \u201cLoading rows\u201d | Table container marked busy; status announces loading | `aria-busy=\"true\"` on table region/container | 4.1.3 |\n| Rows loaded | Row count text updates | Status announces loaded count/page | `role=\"status\"` | 4.1.3 |\n| No rows | Empty state text in table body or adjacent message | Message is readable in normal order | No ARIA needed unless dynamically inserted; status if dynamic | 1.3.1, 4.1.3 |\n| Pagination current page | Current page visually highlighted and text/icon | Current page exposed programmatically | `aria-current=\"page\"` | 4.1.2 |\n| Disabled pagination control | Disabled styling plus text/icon state | Native disabled if `<button>` | `disabled`; use `aria-disabled` only for non-native widgets | 4.1.2 |\n\n### Announcement Region\n\nUse one status region per table, not one live region per cell or header. Multiple live regions inside repeating table structures create noisy and unreliable announcements.\n\nExample announcements:\n\n- \u201cSorted by Revenue, ascending.\u201d\n- \u201cSorted by Region, descending.\u201d\n- \u201cPage 2 of 8 loaded, rows 26 to 50 of 198.\u201d\n- \u201cNo rows match the current filters.\u201d\n\nWCAG citation: WCAG 4.1.3 Status Messages.\n\n---\n\n## Visual Accessibility Plan\n\n### Sort Indicator\n\nThe active sort state must not rely on color alone.\n\nUse at least two of:\n\n- Directional icon.\n- Visible text, such as \u201cSorted ascending.\u201d\n- Visually hidden text for screen reader users.\n- Header background or border.\n- Sort priority number for multi-sort.\n\nIf using arrow icons, mark decorative arrows `aria-hidden=\"true\"` when the state is already communicated through `aria-sort` and text. WCAG 1.1.1 Non-text Content, 1.4.1 Use of Color, 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value.\n\n### Contrast\n\n- Normal text: minimum 4.5:1.\n- Large text: minimum 3:1.\n- Header borders, focus outlines, sort icons, and interactive affordances: minimum 3:1 against adjacent colors.\n- Active sorted header background must still preserve text contrast.\n\nWCAG citations: 1.4.3 Contrast Minimum, 1.4.11 Non-text Contrast.\n\n### Touch and Pointer Targets\n\nSortable header buttons and pagination controls should be at least 24x24 CSS px, with 44x44 CSS px preferred. Header cells may provide larger click areas, but the accessible control must still have a clear name and focus style.\n\nWCAG citation: 2.5.8 Target Size Minimum.\n\n### Reflow and Large Tables\n\nAt 200% and 400% zoom:\n\n- Do not make the whole page horizontally scroll if avoidable.\n- If the data table itself must scroll horizontally, keep the table caption, sort controls, and pagination usable.\n- Preserve access to all columns.\n- Sticky columns/headers must not obscure focused controls.\n- Do not hide sortable functionality at narrow widths.\n\nWCAG citations: 1.4.4 Resize Text, 1.4.10 Reflow, 2.4.11 Focus Not Obscured.\n\n---\n\n## Content Accessibility Plan\n\n### Caption and Context\n\nEvery table needs a caption or nearby heading that clearly identifies the table.\n\nUse:\n\n- `<caption>` for table-specific description.\n- A section heading for page structure.\n- Optional visually hidden instructions only if the interaction is not obvious.\n\nWCAG citations: 1.3.1 Info and Relationships, 2.4.6 Headings and Labels.\n\n### Header Labels\n\nColumn headers must be concise and descriptive.\n\nAvoid vague labels like:\n\n- \u201cValue\u201d\n- \u201cStatus\u201d\n- \u201cData\u201d\n\nUnless context makes them clear.\n\nFor abbreviated headers, provide expanded text visually or programmatically. WCAG 2.4.6 Headings and Labels.\n\n### Row Headers\n\nIf each row has a natural identifier, use `<th scope=\"row\">` for that first identifying cell. This improves screen reader navigation because users hear both row and column context.\n\nWCAG citation: 1.3.1 Info and Relationships.\n\n### Empty and Error States\n\nEmpty state text should be specific:\n\n- \u201cNo rows match the current filters.\u201d\n- \u201cNo revenue data is available for this period.\u201d\n\nError state text should explain recovery:\n\n- \u201cTable data could not be loaded. Try refreshing or changing filters.\u201d\n\nIf dynamically inserted, announce through the table\u2019s status region. WCAG 3.3.1 Error Identification, 4.1.3 Status Messages.\n\n---\n\n## Pagination and Large Data Set Strategy\n\nFor 100+ rows, prefer pagination over making users traverse a very long table.\n\nPagination plan:\n\n- Place pagination after the table.\n- Wrap pagination in `<nav aria-label=\"Table pagination\">`.\n- Use buttons for in-place page changes.\n- Use links if page changes are real URLs.\n- Mark current page with `aria-current=\"page\"`.\n- Disable unavailable previous/next controls using native `disabled` for buttons.\n- Announce page changes through the table status region.\n- Display visible row range text: \u201cShowing 26-50 of 198 rows.\u201d\n\nWCAG citations: 2.1.1 Keyboard, 2.4.4 Link Purpose, 2.4.6 Headings and Labels, 4.1.2 Name Role Value, 4.1.3 Status Messages.\n\nVirtualization warning: if virtualization is used, do not fake total rows with misleading DOM. Screen reader users need accurate row context. If only visible rows are mounted, provide clear visible and programmatic range text. This plan does not claim virtualized tables are impossible; it claims they require explicit testing with target screen readers.\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n### Automated Testing\n\nRun runtime accessibility scans on:\n\n- Initial table state.\n- Ascending sorted state.\n- Descending sorted state.\n- No rows state.\n- Loading state.\n- Paginated state.\n- Multiple tables on one page.\n\nAutomated checks should verify:\n\n- Valid table structure.\n- `th` cells have proper `scope`.\n- Sort buttons have accessible names.\n- No invalid ARIA attributes.\n- Contrast meets requirements.\n- Pagination controls have names and states.\n\nAutomated tools will not reliably verify screen reader announcement quality or whether `aria-sort` is on the correct element, so DOM verification is required.\n\n### DOM Verification\n\nRequired DOM checks:\n\n- Every column header uses `<th scope=\"col\">`.\n- Row headers use `<th scope=\"row\">` when applicable.\n- Sort buttons are inside column header cells.\n- `aria-sort` is applied to the `<th>`, not the button.\n- Only the actively sorted column has `aria-sort=\"ascending\"` or `aria-sort=\"descending\"` in single-sort mode.\n- Decorative icons have `aria-hidden=\"true\"`.\n- Status region exists once per table.\n- Multiple tables have distinct captions, headings, and status regions.\n\n### Keyboard Testing\n\nTest cases:\n\n- Tab reaches each sortable header button in visual order.\n- Enter activates sort.\n- Space activates sort.\n- Focus remains on the activated header after sorting.\n- Focus indicator is visible on every sortable header.\n- Pagination controls are reachable and operable by keyboard.\n- Disabled pagination controls cannot be activated.\n- If row links/buttons exist, they appear in logical row order.\n- No data cell becomes a tab stop unless it contains an actual interactive control.\n\n### Screen Reader Testing\n\nTest with NVDA, JAWS, and VoiceOver:\n\n- Table caption is announced.\n- Column headers are announced with cells.\n- Row headers are announced where present.\n- Sortable headers announce name, role, and sort state.\n- Activating sort announces \u201cSorted by [column], [direction]\u201d through the status region.\n- Pagination announces current page and row range.\n- Multiple tables on one page remain distinguishable.\n\n### Visual Regression\n\nVerify:\n\n- Sort icon and active sorted state are visible.\n- Sort state is not color-only.\n- Focus ring remains visible on header buttons.\n- Layout works at 200% zoom.\n- Table remains usable at 400% zoom or 320px equivalent.\n- High contrast mode preserves header, focus, and sort affordances.\n- Reduced motion does not affect usability if sort transitions are animated.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Tasks\n\n### Task 1: Base Semantic Table\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint after this task**\n\n**Files:**\n\n- Reusable table component file.\n- Table tests.\n- Table documentation examples.\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n\n```html\n<section aria-labelledby=\"table-heading\">\n  <h2 id=\"table-heading\">Table title</h2>\n  <table>\n    <caption>Table description</caption>\n    <thead>\n      <tr>\n        <th scope=\"col\">Column</th>\n      </tr>\n    </thead>\n    <tbody>\n      <tr>\n        <th scope=\"row\">Row label</th>\n        <td>Value</td>\n      </tr>\n    </tbody>\n  </table>\n</section>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n\n- None required for basic table semantics.\n- Use native elements first.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n\n- No custom keyboard interaction.\n- Native reading and screen reader table navigation should work.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Verify semantic table structure.\n- Verify `scope=\"col\"` on column headers.\n- Verify `scope=\"row\"` on row headers when configured.\n- Verify caption exists or table is otherwise clearly labelled.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n\n- 1.3.1 Info and Relationships.\n- 1.3.2 Meaningful Sequence.\n- 2.4.6 Headings and Labels.\n\n---\n\n### Task 2: Sortable Column Headers\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint after this task**\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n\n```html\n<th scope=\"col\" aria-sort=\"ascending\">\n  <button type=\"button\">\n    Revenue\n    <span aria-hidden=\"true\">\u2191</span>\n    <span class=\"visually-hidden\">sorted ascending</span>\n  </button>\n</th>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n\n- `aria-sort` on `<th>`: communicates ascending, descending, none, or other. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- `aria-hidden=\"true\"` on decorative sort icon. WCAG 1.1.1, 4.1.2.\n- Optional `aria-describedby` on button for sort instructions if visible text is insufficient. WCAG 1.3.1.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n\n- Tab focuses sort button.\n- Enter sorts.\n- Space sorts.\n- Focus remains on button after sort.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Verify Enter and Space sort the column.\n- Verify `aria-sort` updates on the correct `<th>`.\n- Verify previous sorted column clears its active `aria-sort`.\n- Verify icon and text match programmatic state.\n- Verify multiple tables do not share IDs or status regions.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n\n- 2.1.1 Keyboard.\n- 2.4.3 Focus Order.\n- 2.4.7 Focus Visible.\n- 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value.\n\n---\n\n### Task 3: Sort Status Announcements\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint after this task**\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n\n```html\n<div role=\"status\" aria-live=\"polite\" aria-atomic=\"true\">\n  Sorted by Revenue, ascending.\n</div>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n\n- `role=\"status\"`: polite status updates. WCAG 4.1.3.\n- `aria-live=\"polite\"`: non-interruptive announcement. WCAG 4.1.3.\n- `aria-atomic=\"true\"`: entire message announced. WCAG 4.1.3.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n\n- No focus movement to the status region.\n- Status updates after sort and pagination actions.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Verify one status region per table.\n- Verify sorting updates the status text.\n- Verify status region is not duplicated per column or row.\n- Verify screen readers announce sort changes.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n\n- 4.1.3 Status Messages.\n- 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value.\n\n---\n\n### Task 4: Pagination for Large Data Sets\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint after this task**\n\n**Structure Stub:**\n\n```html\n<p>Showing rows 26 to 50 of 198.</p>\n\n<nav aria-label=\"Table pagination\">\n  <button type=\"button\">Previous page</button>\n  <button type=\"button\" aria-current=\"page\">2</button>\n  <button type=\"button\">Next page</button>\n</nav>\n```\n\n**ARIA Attributes:**\n\n- `aria-label=\"Table pagination\"` on pagination nav. WCAG 2.4.6.\n- `aria-current=\"page\"` on current page control where appropriate. WCAG 4.1.2.\n- Native `disabled` on unavailable button controls. WCAG 4.1.2.\n\n**Keyboard Interactions:**\n\n- Tab through pagination controls in logical order.\n- Enter/Space activates page buttons.\n- Focus remains on activated pagination control if still present, or moves to equivalent new page control after render.\n- Status region announces new page and row range.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Verify page controls are keyboard operable.\n- Verify current page is programmatically exposed.\n- Verify row range text updates.\n- Verify status announces page changes.\n- Verify focus is not lost after page changes.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n\n- 2.1.1 Keyboard.\n- 2.4.3 Focus Order.\n- 2.4.4 Link Purpose.\n- 2.4.6 Headings and Labels.\n- 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value.\n- 4.1.3 Status Messages.\n\n---\n\n### Task 5: Visual States and Responsive Behavior\n\n\ud83d\udd0d **Review checkpoint after this task**\n\n**Requirements:**\n\n- Sort state uses icon/text, not color alone.\n- Focus indicators meet 3:1 contrast and WCAG 2.4.13 sizing expectations.\n- Header controls are at least 24x24 CSS px, 44x44 preferred.\n- Text and table controls remain usable at 200% and 400% zoom.\n- Sticky headers, if used, do not obscure focused elements.\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Contrast verification.\n- High contrast mode verification.\n- 200% zoom.\n- 400% zoom or 320px equivalent.\n- Focus visibility screenshots.\n- Sort indicator visible without color.\n\n**WCAG Criteria:**\n\n- 1.4.1 Use of Color.\n- 1.4.3 Contrast Minimum.\n- 1.4.10 Reflow.\n- 1.4.11 Non-text Contrast.\n- 2.4.7 Focus Visible.\n- 2.4.11 Focus Not Obscured.\n- 2.4.13 Focus Appearance.\n- 2.5.8 Target Size.\n\n---\n\n## a11y-Critic Review Checkpoints\n\n| Checkpoint | After Task | Focus Areas |\n|---|---|---|\n| \ud83d\udd0d 1 | Base Semantic Table | Verify native table semantics, caption, `scope=\"col\"`, optional `scope=\"row\"`, no inappropriate ARIA roles |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 2 | Sortable Headers | Verify APG Button behavior, `aria-sort` placement on `<th>`, keyboard activation, focus retention |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 3 | Sort Announcements | Verify single status region, useful announcement text, no live regions in loops |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 4 | Pagination | Verify nav labeling, current page state, disabled controls, focus behavior after page changes |\n| \ud83d\udd0d 5 | Visual/Responsive | Verify non-color indicators, contrast, target size, zoom, high contrast, focus visibility |\n\n---\n\n## Architecture Overview\n\nThe component architecture should include:\n\n- One semantic table wrapper per table instance.\n- Native table markup for structure.\n- Sortable header subcomponent using `<th scope=\"col\">` plus nested native `<button>`.\n- Sort state manager supporting single-column sort by default.\n- One status region per table instance.\n- Optional pagination component.\n- Optional row header configuration.\n- No ARIA grid pattern unless the product later requires spreadsheet-like navigation.\n\nARIA patterns used:\n\n- Native table semantics.\n- APG Button pattern for sortable header controls.\n- Status message pattern for sort and pagination announcements.\n- Navigation landmark pattern for pagination.\n\n---\n\n## Failure Modes\n\nThis plan is designed to prevent:\n\n- Using ARIA roles instead of native table elements.\n- Putting `aria-sort` on the button instead of the `<th>`.\n- Making every table cell tabbable.\n- Communicating sort state only with color or an icon.\n- Duplicating live regions inside every header or row.\n- Omitting `scope=\"col\"` or `scope=\"row\"`.\n- Using `role=\"presentation\"` on a real data table.\n- Losing focus after sorting or pagination.\n- Creating ambiguous multiple tables with identical labels/status regions.\n- Hiding pagination or sorting controls at high zoom or narrow viewport.\n- Assuming automated scans verify screen reader sort announcements.\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n- WAI-ARIA Authoring Practices Guide: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/\n- APG Button Pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/button/\n- WCAG 2.2 Quick Reference: https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG22/quickref/\n- WAI Tables Tutorial: https://www.w3.org/WAI/tutorials/tables/\n- MDN `aria-sort`: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Accessibility/ARIA/Reference/Attributes/aria-sort/",
